{eq}\begin{align*}
(2x-b)^2&=5(3x-2)-2x^2+b-5\\
4x^2-4xb+b^2&=15x-10-2x^2+b-5\\
6x^2-4xb-15x+b+15&=0
\end{align*}

{/eq}

By comparing the coefficients of the {eq}x{/eq}-term, we get {eq}-4b=40{/eq} so {eq}b=-10{/eq}. Then, by comparing the constants, we get {eq}b+15=15{/eq} which is satisfied.

Therefore, The value of $a = b^2 = (-10)^2 = \boxed{100}$.
</answer>

